dump: George Beesley gave a summary of the 1999 performance. The safety performance could have been better in the first 6 months, but was significantly improved over the last 6 months of the year. The number of high potential incidents in 1999(4) was significantly improved from 1998 (8). Performance across the platforms was not uniform with one platform having an outstanding performance. It was pointed out that the platforms where DTL is best embedded appear to be the safest.

The                            for 2000 are to work the Well Engineering Safety Plan by using the existing tools and processes with renewed effort. Special focus is to be given to the uniformly application of audit and monitoring mechanisms. It is intended that all managers and supervisors attend the Safety Leadership course by end of Q2.

George Beesley and Ian Lane presented information on the 1999 business performance and showed that a 28% improvement in costs had been achieved.  Average well cost has reduced from 5.6M in 1998 to 4.6m in 1999 with the first well under 2M being achieved by year-end. The reinvestment of the savings achieved resulted in 2 more wells being drilled for the same amount of CAPEX. Performance on TENC and CADA shows a 26% improvement against the planned times and has been outstanding. Brent performance was affected by 3 wells in mid year which incurred substantial losses and hence significantly affected overall performance.  However, progress has been made on the ECD management since then.  It has been identified that there is still room for further improvement in NPT.

Jorn Berget and Maurice White emphasised that 1999 had been an excellent performance especially considering the major unsettling events that occurred associated with the merging of the business units and change out of contractor in Brent.  None of the changes had been easy on staff and they should be very proud of the achievements in 1999.
To improve the safety performance including the cultural aspects where staff will be encouraged to speak up and look out for each other.
Brent depressurisation including losses, ECD management and sand control and which continue to require focus.
Greater focus on Supply Chain Management
Embedding DTL with a mind set change from best achieved performance to best achievable performance.
Ross Richardson advised that a salary increase will be applied for KCA offshore personnel from 1 January 2000.
KCA advised that they are currently conducting a ballot to ascertain whether or not they should recognise a union.

Ian Lane explained how KCA are rewarding proactive safety behaviour.  He explained that using the results from a Climate" survey carried out they have used the workforce feedback in the development of the KCA scheme.  The scheme includes for onsite supervisor to reward good suggestions/actions with quarterly recognition, Managers to make special recognition of achievements (e.g. on offshore visits) and 1,2 and 3 year recognition for crews where no harm to people occurs
EGIS advised that an LTI had occurred at the beginning of the contract.  Following analysis of the occurrence they are promoting a back mechanics initiative.
